              <a href="https://book.douban.com/annotation/31482242/" class="">第37页</a></h3>
          </div>
          <div class="clst">
            <p class="user"><a href="https://www.douban.com/people/shushibi/" class=" " title="猪大勇">猪大勇</a>
                (买买买！吃吃吃！睡睡睡！)
              
                <span class="allstar40" title="推荐"></span>
            </p>
            <div class="reading-note" data-cid="31482242">
              <div class="short">
                
                  <span class="">The primary problem an incumbent faces in the selectorate theory is figure out how to prevent being replaced by challenger

Residents(N)=selectorate&gt;winning coalition&gt;leaders(L) &lt;=&gt; challengers(C)
maintaining collations by taxing and spending in ways that  allocate mixes of public and private goods
The nature of the mix depends on the size of the wining coalition
Total amount spen...</span>
                <p class="pl">
                  <span class="">2014-05-05 10:30</span>
                  
                    &nbsp;&nbsp;<span class="">2人喜欢</span>
                </p>
              </div>
              <div class="all hidden" style="display:none" >
                The primary problem an incumbent faces in the selectorate theory is figure out how to prevent being replaced by challenger<div style="padding-bottom:1em;"></div>Residents(N)=selectorate&gt;winning coalition&gt;leaders(L) &lt;=&gt; challengers(C)<div style="padding-bottom:1em;"></div>maintaining collations by taxing and spending in ways that  allocate mixes of public and private goods<div style="padding-bottom:1em;"></div>The nature of the mix depends on the size of the wining coalition<div style="padding-bottom:1em;"></div>Total amount spent depends on both the size of the selectorate (S) and winning collation (W)<div style="padding-bottom:1em;"></div>Leaders pay for their supporters, when many supporters demanding reward, the cost will be too high<div style="padding-bottom:1em;"></div>selectorate: people express their preference in groups, and may or may not have directly influence the outcome<div style="padding-bottom:1em;"></div>winning coalition: whose support is essential if the incumbent is to remain in power<div style="padding-bottom:1em;"></div>leader or leadership: who have the authority to raise taxes and allocate government funds to pursue chosen policies, including private use of the monies as well as use aimed at the general welfare.<div style="padding-bottom:1em;"></div>Residents: selectorate+disenfranchised group&gt;&gt;disenfranchised group began to shrink (17C)<div style="padding-bottom:1em;"></div>effects of scales (N):<div style="padding-bottom:1em;"></div>1) the larger the scale of a society, the higher the absolute cost of providing public goods<div style="padding-bottom:1em;"></div>2) society’s scale set the number of people who can be taxed by the state&gt;&gt;the magnitude of resources that could be extracted trough taxation<div style="padding-bottom:1em;"></div>Selectorate: easily discerned characteristic: selection of leaders<div style="padding-bottom:1em;"></div>important: they have the opportunity to become a member of a winning  coalition <div style="padding-bottom:1em;"></div>access to valued goods is a fundamental quality of membership in winning coalition<div style="padding-bottom:1em;"></div>scarcity: insurmountable barriers, can be natural or artificial <div style="padding-bottom:1em;"></div>Birthplace: not a great deal in creating scarcity as a quality for selectorate membership <div style="padding-bottom:1em;"></div>Lineage: is sufficient in some societies for entry into the selectorate &gt;&gt; exceedingly scarce<div style="padding-bottom:1em;"></div>**rely on lineage, require a small selectorate&gt;&gt;many society gradually adopted more to the pool of selectorate<div style="padding-bottom:1em;"></div>Special Proficiency: (not directly inheritable) <div style="padding-bottom:1em;"></div>the “specialness” depends on maintaining scarcity of supply &gt;&gt; spread of expertise or military prowess has often been carefully guarded and regulated.<div style="padding-bottom:1em;"></div>the selectorate can be made artificially small.<div style="padding-bottom:1em;"></div>a central an special role in the size of winning coalition (necessary but not sufficient, sometimes only contributory) <div style="padding-bottom:1em;"></div>Religious, skills etc. <div style="padding-bottom:1em;"></div>knowledge-based selectorates are less common than theocratic or weapons-based selectorates<div style="padding-bottom:1em;"></div>Theocratic: coerce their way into political control through the threat of damnation<div style="padding-bottom:1em;"></div>Weapon-based: coerce through their domination over the means of taking lives<div style="padding-bottom:1em;"></div>&gt;&gt;weapon-based is the most common special skill used to determine selectorate membership<div style="padding-bottom:1em;"></div>military prowess and control over arms is a proficiency that can offer its owner the opportunity to provide counsel to civilian leaders<div style="padding-bottom:1em;"></div>leaders have incentives to increase the collective military prowess of the selectorate as a way to ward off revolution: by 1) including military talent in the selectorate or encouraging the members to develop such skill<div style="padding-bottom:1em;"></div>Wealth<div style="padding-bottom:1em;"></div>Land is more scarcer, as it is relatively fixed&gt;&gt;require substantial landholdings to get S smaller<div style="padding-bottom:1em;"></div>Less restricted than lineage or some special proficiency <div style="padding-bottom:1em;"></div>Asset may be dissipated through division among heirs&gt;&gt;&gt;primogeniture as a social means of preserving scarcity of wealth<div style="padding-bottom:1em;"></div>Age and gender<div style="padding-bottom:1em;"></div>Size of Polity<div style="padding-bottom:1em;"></div>Factionalism can be promoted: 1) relationship between such institutions as the selectorate and winning coalition 2) the pool of resources available to the government<div style="padding-bottom:1em;"></div>1) the lager the winning coalition, the more inclined are its leaders to provide public policies that satisfy the welfare of their winning coalition <div style="padding-bottom:1em;"></div>rigged electoral system (USSR) have a large selectorate and small winning coalition (for their own privilege)<div style="padding-bottom:1em;"></div>A leader will make effort to ensure his support understand  that they receive private goods because of his efforts.<div style="padding-bottom:1em;"></div>How much a leader allocate to the public and private depends on institutional constraints=how much revenue is available &gt;&gt;taxation rates/policies<div style="padding-bottom:1em;"></div>Commitment problem <div style="padding-bottom:1em;"></div>the inability of the challenger to guarantee that the prospective defectors will always be members of his winning coalition is a substantial advantage for the incumbent leader (1. W not sure C will provide 2. not sure he can be the leader)<div style="padding-bottom:1em;"></div>Affinity<div style="padding-bottom:1em;"></div>Holding other factors fixed, leader and challenger will chose those who have highest affinity but with lowest cost<div style="padding-bottom:1em;"></div>S will choose the leader who have the highest affinity, holding other factors fixed.<div style="padding-bottom:1em;"></div>&gt;&gt;&gt;leaders have incumbency advantage, as potential defectors do not know if they will be better off or not under challengers. the advantage depends on the size of W, and the size of S, not on affinity<div style="padding-bottom:1em;"></div>Affinity is more dispersed in heterogeneous society rather than homogeneous society<div style="padding-bottom:1em;"></div>Affinity may have the potential to create what are effectively small winning-coaliion system even thought the legal or constitutional system dictate majority rule.&gt;&gt;&gt;key member that can deliver bloc votes<div style="padding-bottom:1em;"></div>blocs can reduce the commitment problem<div style="padding-bottom:1em;"></div>risk of being excluded is the main factor in this theory<div style="padding-bottom:1em;"></div>loyalty norm W/S<div style="padding-bottom:1em;"></div>either the size of W is shrinking or the size of S is growing, defector is riskier<div style="padding-bottom:1em;"></div>The smaller W/S is, the less inclined any member of the coalition is to put private benefits at risk by giving support to a opponent<div style="padding-bottom:1em;"></div>&gt;&gt; member prefer larger W/S (larger W, smaller S) &gt;&gt; migration,revolutions …etc <div style="padding-bottom:1em;"></div>what is missing:<div style="padding-bottom:1em;"></div>1) leader acts as an individual with sole control over policy<div style="padding-bottom:1em;"></div>2) the implementation of policy is never problematic<div style="padding-bottom:1em;"></div>3) Public goods are normal goods, the more the better (ideology only in the extent of affinity)<div style="padding-bottom:1em;"></div>4) all people are identical except for their affinities for one another 

